ura, Skopje, {{ISBN|9989-32-067-5}} (original edition: Arlea, Paris, 1992).\n* Albert Sonnichsen, ''Confessions of a Macedonian Bandit: A Californian in the Balkan Wars'', The Narrative Press, {{ISBN|1-58976-237-1}}. Also here [https://web.archive.org/web/20010601035630/http://library.ferris.edu/~cochranr/stone/stone2c3.htm ''Confessions'', Ch. XXIV] {{in lang|en}}, and Macedonian translation.\n* Fikret Adanir, ''Die Makedonische Frage'', Wiesbaden, 1979.\n* \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d \u041f\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0432, \"\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e-\u043e\u0441\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u041e\u0434\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\", \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, 1979.\n* Ivo Banac, \"The Macedoine\", pp.&nbsp;307\u2013328 in of ''The National Question in Yugoslavia. Origins, History, Politics'', Cornell University Press, 1984.\n* H. N. Brailsford, ''Macedonia: its races and their future'', Methuen & Co., London, 1906 ([http://www.promacedonia.org/en/hb/hb_photo.html Brailsford's photos])\n* \u0425\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0421\u0438\u043b\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432, \"\u041e\u0441\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u043d\u0438\u0442e \u0431\u043e\u0440\u0431\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f\", \u0442\u043e\u043c I \u0438 II, \u0438\u0437\u0434. \u043d\u0430 \u0418\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u041e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f, \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, 1933 \u0438 1943, also volume I\n* \u041b\u044e\u0431\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0440\u044a \u041c\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0447\u044a, \"\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u044a 1913 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430\", \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0438\u0442\u0435, \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, \u0414\u044a\u0440\u0436\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0447\u0430\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430, 1918 \u0433.,\n* \"\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f. \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u044a\u0434\u0431\u0430\", \u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u043d\u0430 \u041c\u041d\u0418 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0444. \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432, \u0442\u043e\u043c I, II \u0438 III, \u0438\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u0417\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\", \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, 1998.\n* \"\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f \u2013 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u044b \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b\", \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0410\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a, \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430, 1999 (includes \u0420. \u041f. \u0413\u0440\u0438\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430, \"\u0424\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u0437\u0433\u043b\u044f\u0434\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441 \u0432 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435 1922\u20131924 \u0433\u0433.\"), the complete symposium\n* \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432, \"\u041a\u043e\u0438 \u0431\u0435\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432\u043e \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430\", \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043fje, 1998. {{in lang|mk}}\n* Palmer, S. and R. King, ''Yugoslav Communism and the Macedonian Question'', Archon Books, 1971.\n* \u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0438\u043d \u041c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0432, \"\u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b\u043d\u043e \u0434\u0435\u043b\u043e \u0432 \u044e\u0433\u043e\u0437\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f (1941\u20131944 \u0433.)\", \"\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0433\u043b\u0435\u0434\", 1, 1998. {{in lang|bg}}\n* Keith Brown, ''The Past in Question: Modern Macedonia and the Uncertainties of Nation'', Princeton University Press, 2003.\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|IMRO}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040210185155/http://www.vmro-dpmne.org.mk/index.asp Website of Macedonian VMRO-DPMNE] {{in lang|mk|en}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061022043326/http://www.makedonskaistorija.com/media/1/20050517-UstavBMORKw.jpg The statute of BMARC from a Macedonian language website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050210165854/http://www.bulgaria.com/VMRO/bmork.htm The complete statute of BMARC]\n\n=== English ===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181228125103/http://macedoniagreece.com/ History of the Greek-Macedonian Fighters (\u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03c7\u03bf\u03b9 \u2013 Makedonomachi), adversaries of the IMRO]\n\n=== Bulgarian ===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180810001146/http://vmro.org/ Website of Bulgarian VMRO-BND]\n\n=== Macedonian ===\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/super2/vmro-istorija/index.html Macedonian site about history of IMRO \u2013 includes Dr. Tatarchev's complete memoirs]\n\n[[Category:Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization| ]]\n[[Category:Kosovo Vilayet]]\n[[Category:Manastir Vilayet]]\n[[Category:Salonica Vilayet]]\n[[Category:Adrianople Vilayet]]\n[[Category:1893 establishments in the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "name_user": "StanProg", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation;wording;grammar;tautology", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internal_Macedonian_Revolutionary_Organization"}
{"title_page": "Mark A. Milley", "text_new": "{{short description|United States general}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|image= General Mark A. Milley.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Milley in 2019\n|nickname=\n|birth_name=Mark Alexander Milley\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1958|6|18}}\n|birth_place= [[Winchester, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1980\u2013present\n|rank= [[General (United States)|General]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]]<br/>[[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[United States Army Forces Command]]<br/>[[III Corps (United States)|III Corps]]<br/>[[International Security Assistance Force]] Joint Command<br/>[[10th Mountain Division (United States)|10th Mountain Division]]<br/>[[2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (United States)|2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (Light)]]\n|battles= [[Operation Just Cause]]<br/>[[Operation Uphold Democracy]]<br/>[[Implementation Force|Operation Joint Endeavor]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]<br/>[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u201314)|War in Afghanistan]]\n|awards= {{nowrap|[[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)}}<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (4)<br/>[[Defense Superior Service Medal]] (3)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (3)<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (4)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Mark Alexander Milley''' (born June 18, 1958) is a [[United States Army]] general and the 20th [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]]. As Chairman, he is the highest-ranking and senior-most military officer in the United States Armed Forces. He previously served as 39th [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Chief of Staff of the Army]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/leaders/csa/?from=wiki |title=Chief of Staff of the Army &#124; General Mark A. Milley |publisher=United States Army |date= |accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Winchester, Massachusetts]], Milley attended the [[Belmont Hill School]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Berkowitz |first=Bram |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Winchester Native Mark A. Milley Becomes U.S. Army Chief of Staff |url=http://winchester.wickedlocal.com/article/20150827/NEWS/150827482 |newspaper=Winchester Star |location=Winchester, MA}}</ref> He holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in politics from [[Princeton University]], a [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|Master of Arts]] degree in [[international relations]] from [[Columbia University]], and another Master of Arts degree in [[national security]] and [[strategic studies]] from the [[United States Naval War College]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/gen_milley/gen_milley.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-08-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906014951/http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/GEN_Milley/GEN_Milley.htm |archivedate=2015-09-06}}</ref> He is also a graduate of the [[MIT Center for International Studies]] Seminar XXI National Security Studies Program.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://semxxi.mit.edu/about/messages/from-the-director |title=From the Director: September, 2015 |last=Art |first=Robert |date=September 1, 2015 |website=MIT Seminar XXI |publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n[[File:Mark Miley Army Chief of Staff.jpg|thumb|upright|Mark Milley as Army Chief of Staff]]\nAlthough Milley earned his [[Officer (armed forces)|commission]] as an [[Armor Branch (United States)|Armor]] officer through Princeton's Army [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] program in 1980, he has spent most of his career in [[Infantry Branch (United States)|Infantry]] assignments.<ref>{{cite web|last=Graham-Ashley |first=Heather |url=http://www.army.mil/article/93394 |title=III Corps' new commander views road ahead, training, support |publisher=III Corps and Fort Hood Public Affairs |date=December 20, 2012 |accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMilley has served in the [[82nd Airborne Division]], the [[5th Special Forces Group]],<ref>Gal Perl Finkel, [https://www.jpost.com/Opinion/The-IDF-that-Eisenkot-leaves-behind-is-ready-575993 The IDF that Eisenkot leaves behind is ready], ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', January 1, 2019.</ref> the [[7th Infantry Division (United States)|7th Infantry Division]], the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]], the [[Fort Polk|Joint Readiness Training Center]], the [[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th Infantry Division]], Operations Staff of the Joint Staff, and as a Military Assistant to the Secretary of Defense in the Pentagon.<ref>[http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/GEN_Milley/GEN_Milley.htm U.S. Army Forces Command, Commanding General] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906014951/http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/GEN_Milley/GEN_Milley.htm |date=2015-09-06}}, www.army.mil/forscom, dated August 15, 2014, last accessed August 15, 2015</ref> In November 2000, he participated in the 2nd Annual Army-Navy Ice Hockey Game in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], a charity event benefiting youth ice hockey players in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2000/11/08/sports/hawaiibeat.html|title=Honolulu Star-Bulletin Sports |website=archives.starbulletin.com}}</ref>\n\nGeneral Milley has had multiple command and staff positions in eight divisions and Special Forces throughout the last 39 years to include command of the 1st Battalion, 506th Infantry, 2nd Infantry Division;  Milley commanded the [[2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (United States)|2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (Light)]] from December 2003 to July 2005, served as Deputy Commanding General (Operations), [[101st Airborne Division]] from July 2007 to April 2008, and was Commander of the [[10th Mountain Division]] from November 2011 to December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last=Block |first=Gordon |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20121204/NEWS03/712049844 |title=Fort Drum welcomes new 10th Mountain Division commander at ceremony |publisher=Watertown Daily Times |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=January 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914203322/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20121204/NEWS03/712049844 |archive-date=September 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then served as the Commanding General of [[III Corps (United States)|III Corps]], based at [[Fort Hood]], Texas, from 2012 to 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armytimes.com/story/military/pentagon/2015/05/13/new-army-chief-of-staff-named/27232781/|title=Gen. Mark Milley picked for Army chief of staff|author=Michelle Tan, Staff writer|date=May 13, 2015|work=Army Times}}</ref> and as the Commanding General of [[United States Army Forces Command]], based at [[Fort Bragg]], North Carolina, from 2014 to 2015. He was appointed [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]] on August 14, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.armytimes.com/story/military/pentagon/2015/08/14/milley-takes-over-new-chief-staff-odierno-retires/31728117/ |title=Milley takes over as new chief of staff; Odierno retires|author=Michelle Tan, Staff writer|date=August 14, 2015|work=Army Times}}</ref>\n\n===Iraq War study===\n[[File:Pentagon 9-11 remembrance ceremony 170911-D-SV709-662 (36332657404).jpg|thumb|President [[Donald Trump]] shakes hands with General Mark Milley following the 9/11 Observance Ceremony at the Pentagon in Arlington, Va., September 11, 2017]]\nIn 2018, Milley was involved in deciding whether the Army would publish a controversial study on the Iraq War. Milley reportedly decided that he wanted to read the two-volume, 1,300-page, 500,000-word study before making a decision.  Milley also directed that an external panel of scholars review the work. After the panel returned glowing reviews on the study, including one that described the study as \"the gold standard in official history,\" Milley continued to delay publication so he could review the study further.\n\nIn September 2018, [[United States Secretary of the Army|Secretary of the Army]] [[Mark Esper]] and other Army officials decided to distance themselves from the study by casting the study \"as an independent\" work of the authors, instead of being described as a project by the Chief of Staff of the Army's Operation Iraqi Freedom Study Group.\" When confronted by a journalist from the ''Wall Street Journal'' in October 2018, Milley reversed these decisions, ordering the study to be published officially, and with a foreword that he would write. He declared the team that wrote the study \"did a damn good job,\" that the study itself was \"a solid work,\" and noted that he aimed to publish the study by the holidays (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-army-ordered-an-unvarnished-iraq-war-historythen-let-it-languish-1540220153|title=The Army Stymied Its Own Study of the Iraq War|first=Michael R. |last=Gordon|date=October 22, 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\nWithin days of this revelation, two members of Congress who sit on the House Armed Services Committee (Reps. [[Jackie Speier]], D-California, and [[Ruben Gallego]], D-Arizona) sent a letter to Army leaders expressing their anger over the delay. In a press release accompanying the letter to Milley and Esper, Rep. Spier said, \"This is simply the Army being unwilling to publicly air its mistakes. Our military, Congress, and the American people deserve nothing less than total transparency on the lessons the Army has identified so that we may use those lessons to avoid costly, and too often deadly, mistakes of the past.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/10/25/armys-detailed-iraq-war-study-remains-unpublished-years-after-completion/|title=Army\u2019s detailed Iraq war study remains unpublished years after completion|first=Todd |last=South|date=October 25, 2018|website=Army Times}}</ref> The study was published January 17, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102142425/https://ssi.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/display.cfm?pubID=1373|title=The U.S. Army in the Iraq War|last=|first=|date=January 17, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff===\n[[File:Office Call 191031-A-PZ314-132.jpg|thumb|right|Gen. Milley at the Pentagon as [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], October 30, 2019]]\n[[File:Esper Tours WWII Bois Jacques Foxhole Site in Belgium.jpg|thumb|Gen. Milley, Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and members of the [[101st Airborne Division]] tour the ''[[Foy, Belgium|Bois Jacques]]'' during the 75th anniversary of the [[Battle of the Bulge]], 2019]]\nOn December 8, 2018, President [[Donald Trump]] announced that he would nominate Milley to serve as [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/12/08/trump-says-gen-mark-milley-chair-joint-chiefs-staff/2249369002/|title=Donald Trump makes it official: Gen. Mark Milley to chair Joint Chiefs of Staff|website=USA Today|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Bowman | first1=Tom | title=Meet Mark Milley, Trump's Pick For Joint Chiefs Chairman | url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/08/674935309/meet-mark-milley-trumps-pick-for-joint-chiefs-chairman | date=December 8, 2019 | work=[[NPR]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> On July 25, 2019, the United States Senate confirmed Milley's nomination by a vote of 89\u20131,<ref>[https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=116&session=1&vote=00230 On the Nomination (Confirmation: General Mark A. Milley to be Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff), United States Senate, July 25, 2019]</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Cooper | first1=Helene | title=How Mark Milley, a General Who Mixes Bluntness and Banter, Became Trump\u2019s Top Military Adviser | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/29/us/politics/mark-milley-chairman-joint-chiefs.html | date=September 29, 2019 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> and he was sworn in on September 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Macias | first1=Amanda | title=Trump oversees swearing-in of Gen. Mark Milley as the new chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/30/trump-watches-as-gen-mark-milley-becomes-chairman-of-joint-chiefs.html | date=September 30, 2019 | work=[[CNBC]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Babb | first1=Carla | title=New Top US Military Officer Takes Helm Amid Iran Tensions, Afghan Violence | url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/new-top-us-military-officer-takes-helm-amid-iran-tensions-afghan-violence | date=September 30, 2019 | work=[[Voice of America]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Baldor | first1=Lolita C. | title=Gen. Milley faces challenges as next Joint Chiefs chairman | url=https://www.apnews.com/58a1cfe95c50432e9e0964f7f075211d | date=September 30, 2019 | work=[[Associated Press]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Golby | first1=Jim | title=President Trump tapped Gen. Mark Milley as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. Here are 3 things to know. | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/10/01/president-trump-tapped-gen-mark-milley-chairman-joint-chiefs-staff-here-are-things-know/ | date=October 1, 2019 | work=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter attending 75th anniversary commemorations of the [[Battle of the Bulge]] in Belgium and Luxembourg on December 16, 2019, Milley met with the Russian military chief of staff [[Valery Gerasimov]] in [[Bern, Switzerland]], on December 18. This continued a series of regular meetings between the American and Russian military chiefs reestablished by Milley's predecessor [[Joseph Dunford]] in 2017 to ensure open communication and avoid conflict, especially in [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite news | last1=Detsch | first1=Jack | title=Intel: Top US and Russian generals link up to talk Syria | url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/russia-us-generals-talk-syria-military-gerasimov-milley.html | date=December 18, 2019 | website=Al-Monitor | accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref> The face-to-face meeting was arranged with the assistance of the incoming Swiss military chief Thomas S\u00fcssli.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Hashmi | first1=Faizan | title=Russian General Staff Chief, Top Swiss Army Commander Meet In Bern - Defense Ministry | url=https://www.urdupoint.com/en/world/russian-general-staff-chief-top-swiss-army-c-790924.html | date=December 19, 2019 | website=UrduPoint Network | accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Operational deployments===\nMilley has had multiple operational deployments including:\n* [[Multinational Force and Observers]], [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]], Egypt\n* [[United States invasion of Panama|Operation Just Cause]], [[Panama]]\n* [[Operation Uphold Democracy]], [[Haiti]]\n* [[Implementation Force (IFOR)|Operation Joint Endeavor]], [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]]\n* [[Iraq War|Operation Iraqi Freedom]], Iraq\n* [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Operation Enduring Freedom]], Afghanistan\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:CIB2.svg|125px]] [[Combat Infantryman Badge]] with Star ''(denoting 2nd award)''\n|-\n|[[File:Expert Infantry Badge.svg|125px]] [[Expert Infantryman Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Einzelbild Special Forces (Special Forces Insignia).svg|85px]] [[Special Forces Tab]]\n|-\n|[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|75px]] [[Ranger tab]]\n|-\n|[[File:Master Parachutist badge (United States).svg|80px]] [[Parachutist Badge (United States)|Master Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:SFDiver.PNG|65px]] [[Diver insignia|Special Operations Diver Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Joint Chiefs of Staff seal.svg|90px]] [[Joint Chiefs of Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Army Staff Identification Badge.png|78px]] [[Army Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Brevet Parachutiste.jpg|100px]] French [[Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:101st Airborne Division CSIB.png|75px]] [[101st Airborne Division]] [[Combat Service Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Distinctive unit insignia of the 506th Infantry Regiment (United States).svg|50px]] [[506th Infantry Regiment (United States)|506th Infantry Regiment]] [[Distinctive Unit Insignia]]\n|-\n|[[File:ArmyOSB.svg|50px]] 10 [[Overseas Service Bar]]s\n|}\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] with one bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-48px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-36px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-24px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] with three oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=US Defense Superior Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-42px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-30px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Defense Superior Service Medal]] with two bronze oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-42px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-30px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Legion of Merit]] with two oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|name=Bronze Star ribbon|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-48px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-36px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-24px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Bronze Star Medal]] with three oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=5|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious Service ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] with silver oak leaf cluster\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army Commendation Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-43px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-31px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-19px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-55px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Army Commendation Medal]] with four oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Army Achievement Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Army Achievement Medal]] with oak leaf cluster\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Joint Meritorious Unit Award ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Joint Meritorious Unit Award]] with oak leaf cluster\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Meritorious_Unit_Commendation_ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-48px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-36px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-24px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Meritorious Unit Commendation]] with three oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[National Defense Service Medal]] with one bronze [[service star]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=AFEMRib.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-41px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d-vector.svg|11px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-30px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d-vector.svg|11px]]</span> [[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]] with two service stars\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|name=Afghanistan Campaign ribbon|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-47px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d-vector.svg|11px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-36px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d-vector.svg|11px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-25px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d-vector.svg|11px]]</span> [[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]] with three [[campaign star]]s\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-41px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d-vector.svg|11px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-30px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze-service-star-3d-vector.svg|11px]]</span> [[Iraq Campaign Medal]] with two campaign stars\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Korea Defense Service ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Korea Defense Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|name=Humanitarian Service ribbon|width=60}} [[Humanitarian Service Medal]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Army Service Ribbon]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Army Overseas Service Ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top: 0px; left: -36px; display: inline-block; width: 0;\">[[File:Award numeral 5.png|11px]]</span> [[Overseas Service Ribbon#Army|Army Overseas Service Ribbon]] with bronze [[award numeral]] 5\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=NATO Medal ISAF ribbon bar.svg|width=60}} [[NATO Medal]] for service with [[ISAF]] with bronze service star\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=MFO Ribbon bar.svg|width=60}} [[Multinational Force and Observers Medal]]\n|-\n|[[File:Ordre national du Merite Commandeur ribbon.svg|60px]] [[National Order of Merit (France)|French National Order of Merit]], Commander<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/USEmbassyFrance/status/1061674118314147841 |title=U.S. Embassy France |publisher=Twitter.com |date=November 11, 2018 |accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mark A. Milley}}\n* {{US_Army|url=http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/gen_milley/gen_milley.htm|article=Lieutenant General Mark A. Milley}}\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-mil}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[James L. Terry|James Terry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Commanding General of the [[10th Mountain Division (United States)|10th Mountain Division]]|years=2011\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen J. Townsend|Stephen Townsend]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Donald M. Campbell, Jr.|Donald Campbell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Commanding General of [[III Corps (United States)|III Corps]]|years=2012\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sean MacFarland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[James L. Terry|James Terry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Commanding General of [[International Security Assistance Force|ISAF-Joint Command]]|years=2013\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Joseph Anderson (U.S. Army general)|Joseph Anderson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Daniel B. Allyn|Daniel Allyn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Commanding General of [[United States Army Forces Command]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert B. Abrams]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Raymond T. Odierno]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]|years=2015\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James C. McConville]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Joseph Dunford]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|us}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barbara Barrett]]|as=[[Secretary of the Air Force]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]<br />''{{small|as Chair of the Joint Chiefs of Staff}}''|years=}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jerome Powell]]|as=Chair of the Federal Reserve}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current JCS members}}\n{{CJCS}}\n{{US Army Chiefs of Staff}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milley, Mark A.}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:Belmont Hill School alumni]]\n[[Category:School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States Army Special Forces]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Naval War College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Winchester, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Princeton Tigers men's ice hockey players]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Meritorious Service Medal (United States)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|United States general}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|image= General Mark A. Milley.jpg\n|image_size= \n|alt= \n|caption= Milley in 2019\n|nickname=\n|birth_name=Mark Alexander Milley\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1958|6|18}}\n|birth_place= [[Winchester, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date= \n|death_place= \n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1980\u2013present\n|rank= [[General (United States)|General]]\n|unit= \n|commands= [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]]<br/>[[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]]<br/>[[United States Army Forces Command]]<br/>[[III Corps (United States)|III Corps]]<br/>[[International Security Assistance Force]] Joint Command<br/>[[10th Mountain Division (United States)|10th Mountain Division]]<br/>[[2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (United States)|2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (Light)]]\n|battles= [[Operation Just Cause]]<br/>[[Operation Uphold Democracy]]<br/>[[Implementation Force|Operation Joint Endeavor]]<br/>[[Iraq War]]<br/>[[War in Afghanistan (2001\u201314)|War in Afghanistan]]\n|awards= [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] (2)<br/>[[Army Distinguished Service Medal]] (4)<br/>[[Defense Superior Service Medal]] (3)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (3)<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (4)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''Mark Alexander Milley''' (born June 18, 1958) is a [[United States Army]] General and the 20th [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], and is, as such, the highest-ranking and senior-most military officer in the United States Armed Forces. \n\nHe previously served as 39th [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army|Chief of Staff of the Army]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.army.mil/leaders/csa/?from=wiki |title=Chief of Staff of the Army &#124; General Mark A. Milley |publisher=United States Army |date= |accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Winchester, Massachusetts]], Milley attended the [[Belmont Hill School]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Berkowitz |first=Bram |date=August 27, 2015 |title=Winchester Native Mark A. Milley Becomes U.S. Army Chief of Staff |url=http://winchester.wickedlocal.com/article/20150827/NEWS/150827482 |newspaper=Winchester Star |location=Winchester, MA}}</ref> He holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in politics from [[Princeton University]], a [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|Master of Arts]] degree in [[international relations]] from [[Columbia University]], and another Master of Arts degree in [[national security]] and [[strategic studies]] from the [[United States Naval War College]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/gen_milley/gen_milley.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-08-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906014951/http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/GEN_Milley/GEN_Milley.htm |archivedate=2015-09-06}}</ref> He is also a graduate of the [[MIT Center for International Studies]] Seminar XXI National Security Studies Program.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://semxxi.mit.edu/about/messages/from-the-director |title=From the Director: September, 2015 |last=Art |first=Robert |date=September 1, 2015 |website=MIT Seminar XXI |publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref>\n\n==Military career==\n[[File:Mark Miley Army Chief of Staff.jpg|thumb|upright|Mark Milley as Army Chief of Staff]]\nAlthough Milley earned his [[Officer (armed forces)|commission]] as an [[Armor Branch (United States)|Armor]] officer through Princeton's Army [[Reserve Officers' Training Corps]] program in 1980, he has spent most of his career in [[Infantry Branch (United States)|Infantry]] assignments.<ref>{{cite web|last=Graham-Ashley |first=Heather |url=http://www.army.mil/article/93394 |title=III Corps' new commander views road ahead, training, support |publisher=III Corps and Fort Hood Public Affairs |date=December 20, 2012 |accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMilley has served in the [[82nd Airborne Division]], the [[5th Special Forces Group]],<ref>Gal Perl Finkel, [https://www.jpost.com/Opinion/The-IDF-that-Eisenkot-leaves-behind-is-ready-575993 The IDF that Eisenkot leaves behind is ready], ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', January 1, 2019.</ref> the [[7th Infantry Division (United States)|7th Infantry Division]], the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)|2nd Infantry Division]], the [[Fort Polk|Joint Readiness Training Center]], the [[25th Infantry Division (United States)|25th Infantry Division]], Operations Staff of the Joint Staff, and as a Military Assistant to the Secretary of Defense in the Pentagon.<ref>[http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/GEN_Milley/GEN_Milley.htm U.S. Army Forces Command, Commanding General] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906014951/http://www.forscom.army.mil/cmd_staff/GEN_Milley/GEN_Milley.htm |date=2015-09-06}}, www.army.mil/forscom, dated August 15, 2014, last accessed August 15, 2015</ref> In November 2000, he participated in the 2nd Annual Army-Navy Ice Hockey Game in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], a charity event benefiting youth ice hockey players in the area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2000/11/08/sports/hawaiibeat.html|title=Honolulu Star-Bulletin Sports |website=archives.starbulletin.com}}</ref>\n\nGeneral Milley has had multiple command and staff positions in eight divisions and Special Forces throughout the last 39 years to include command of the 1st Battalion, 506th Infantry, 2nd Infantry Division;  Milley commanded the [[2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (United States)|2nd Brigade Combat Team, 10th Mountain Division (Light)]] from December 2003 to July 2005, served as Deputy Commanding General (Operations), [[101st Airborne Division]] from July 2007 to April 2008, and was Commander of the [[10th Mountain Division]] from November 2011 to December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |last=Block |first=Gordon |url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20121204/NEWS03/712049844 |title=Fort Drum welcomes new 10th Mountain Division commander at ceremony |publisher=Watertown Daily Times |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=January 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914203322/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20121204/NEWS03/712049844 |archive-date=September 14, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then served as the Commanding General of [[III Corps (United States)|III Corps]], based at [[Fort Hood]], Texas, from 2012 to 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armytimes.com/story/military/pentagon/2015/05/13/new-army-chief-of-staff-named/27232781/|title=Gen. Mark Milley picked for Army chief of staff|author=Michelle Tan, Staff writer|date=May 13, 2015|work=Army Times}}</ref> and as the Commanding General of [[United States Army Forces Command]], based at [[Fort Bragg]], North Carolina, from 2014 to 2015. He was appointed [[Chief of Staff of the United States Army]] on August 14, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.armytimes.com/story/military/pentagon/2015/08/14/milley-takes-over-new-chief-staff-odierno-retires/31728117/ |title=Milley takes over as new chief of staff; Odierno retires|author=Michelle Tan, Staff writer|date=August 14, 2015|work=Army Times}}</ref>\n\n===Iraq War study===\n[[File:Pentagon 9-11 remembrance ceremony 170911-D-SV709-662 (36332657404).jpg|thumb|President [[Donald Trump]] shakes hands with General Mark Milley following the 9/11 Observance Ceremony at the Pentagon in Arlington, Va., September 11, 2017]]\nIn 2018, Milley was involved in deciding whether the Army would publish a controversial study on the Iraq War. Milley reportedly decided that he wanted to read the two-volume, 1,300-page, 500,000-word study before making a decision.  Milley also directed that an external panel of scholars review the work. After the panel returned glowing reviews on the study, including one that described the study as \"the gold standard in official history,\" Milley continued to delay publication so he could review the study further.\n\nIn September 2018, [[United States Secretary of the Army|Secretary of the Army]] [[Mark Esper]] and other Army officials decided to distance themselves from the study by casting the study \"as an independent\" work of the authors, instead of being described as a project by the Chief of Staff of the Army's Operation Iraqi Freedom Study Group.\" When confronted by a journalist from the ''Wall Street Journal'' in October 2018, Milley reversed these decisions, ordering the study to be published officially, and with a foreword that he would write. He declared the team that wrote the study \"did a damn good job,\" that the study itself was \"a solid work,\" and noted that he aimed to publish the study by the holidays (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-army-ordered-an-unvarnished-iraq-war-historythen-let-it-languish-1540220153|title=The Army Stymied Its Own Study of the Iraq War|first=Michael R. |last=Gordon|date=October 22, 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref>\n\nWithin days of this revelation, two members of Congress who sit on the House Armed Services Committee (Reps. [[Jackie Speier]], D-California, and [[Ruben Gallego]], D-Arizona) sent a letter to Army leaders expressing their anger over the delay. In a press release accompanying the letter to Milley and Esper, Rep. Spier said, \"This is simply the Army being unwilling to publicly air its mistakes. Our military, Congress, and the American people deserve nothing less than total transparency on the lessons the Army has identified so that we may use those lessons to avoid costly, and too often deadly, mistakes of the past.\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2018/10/25/armys-detailed-iraq-war-study-remains-unpublished-years-after-completion/|title=Army\u2019s detailed Iraq war study remains unpublished years after completion|first=Todd |last=South|date=October 25, 2018|website=Army Times}}</ref> The study was published January 17, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102142425/https://ssi.armywarcollege.edu/pubs/display.cfm?pubID=1373|title=The U.S. Army in the Iraq War|last=|first=|date=January 17, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff===\n[[File:Office Call 191031-A-PZ314-132.jpg|thumb|right|Gen. Milley at the Pentagon as [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]], October 30, 2019]]\n[[File:Esper Tours WWII Bois Jacques Foxhole Site in Belgium.jpg|thumb|Gen. Milley, Defense Secretary [[Mark Esper]], and members of the [[101st Airborne Division]] tour the ''[[Foy, Belgium|Bois Jacques]]'' during the 75th anniversary of the [[Battle of the Bulge]], 2019]]\nOn December 8, 2018, President [[Donald Trump]] announced that he would nominate Milley to serve as [[Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/12/08/trump-says-gen-mark-milley-chair-joint-chiefs-staff/2249369002/|title=Donald Trump makes it official: Gen. Mark Milley to chair Joint Chiefs of Staff|website=USA Today|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Bowman | first1=Tom | title=Meet Mark Milley, Trump's Pick For Joint Chiefs Chairman | url=https://www.npr.org/2018/12/08/674935309/meet-mark-milley-trumps-pick-for-joint-chiefs-chairman | date=December 8, 2019 | work=[[NPR]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> On July 25, 2019, the United States Senate confirmed Milley's nomination by a vote of 89\u20131,<ref>[https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=116&session=1&vote=00230 On the Nomination (Confirmation: General Mark A. Milley to be Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff), United States Senate, July 25, 2019]</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Cooper | first1=Helene | title=How Mark Milley, a General Who Mixes Bluntness and Banter, Became Trump\u2019s Top Military Adviser | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/29/us/politics/mark-milley-chairman-joint-chiefs.html | date=September 29, 2019 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref> and he was sworn in on September 30, 2019.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Macias | first1=Amanda | title=Trump oversees swearing-in of Gen. Mark Milley as the new chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/09/30/trump-watches-as-gen-mark-milley-becomes-chairman-of-joint-chiefs.html | date=September 30, 2019 | work=[[CNBC]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Babb | first1=Carla | title=New Top US Military Officer Takes Helm Amid Iran Tensions, Afghan Violence | url=https://www.voanews.com/usa/new-top-us-military-officer-takes-helm-amid-iran-tensions-afghan-violence | date=September 30, 2019 | work=[[Voice of America]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Baldor | first1=Lolita C. | title=Gen. Milley faces challenges as next Joint Chiefs chairman | url=https://www.apnews.com/58a1cfe95c50432e9e0964f7f075211d | date=September 30, 2019 | work=[[Associated Press]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Golby | first1=Jim | title=President Trump tapped Gen. Mark Milley as chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. Here are 3 things to know. | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/10/01/president-trump-tapped-gen-mark-milley-chairman-joint-chiefs-staff-here-are-things-know/ | date=October 1, 2019 | work=[[The Washington Post]] | accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter attending 75th anniversary commemorations of the [[Battle of the Bulge]] in Belgium and Luxembourg on December 16, 2019, Milley met with the Russian military chief of staff [[Valery Gerasimov]] in [[Bern, Switzerland]], on December 18. This continued a series of regular meetings between the American and Russian military chiefs reestablished by Milley's predecessor [[Joseph Dunford]] in 2017 to ensure open communication and avoid conflict, especially in [[Syria]].<ref>{{cite news | last1=Detsch | first1=Jack | title=Intel: Top US and Russian generals link up to talk Syria | url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2019/12/russia-us-generals-talk-syria-military-gerasimov-milley.html | date=December 18, 2019 | website=Al-Monitor | accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref> The face-to-face meeting was arranged with the assistance of the incoming Swiss military chief Thomas S\u00fcssli.<ref>{{cite news | last1=Hashmi | first1=Faizan | title=Russian General Staff Chief, Top Swiss Army Commander Meet In Bern - Defense Ministry | url=https://www.urdupoint.com/en/world/russian-general-staff-chief-top-swiss-army-c-790924.html | date=December 19, 2019 | website=UrduPoint Network | accessdate=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Operational deployments===\nMilley has had multiple operational deployments including:\n* [[Multinational Force and Observers]], [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]], Egypt\n* [[United States invasion of Panama|Operation Just Cause]], [[Panama]]\n* [[Operation Uphold Democracy]], [[Haiti]]\n* [[Implementation Force (IFOR)|Operation Joint Endeavor]], [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]]\n* [[Iraq War|Operation Iraqi Freedom]], Iraq\n* [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Operation Enduring Freedom]], Afghanistan\n\n==Awards and decorations==\n{|\n|-\n|[[File:CIB2.svg|125px]] [[Combat Infantryman Badge]] with Star ''(denoting 2nd award)''\n|-\n|[[File:Expert Infantry Badge.svg|125px]] [[Expert Infantryman Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Einzelbild Special Forces (Special Forces Insignia).svg|85px]] [[Special Forces Tab]]\n|-\n|[[File:Ranger Tab.svg|75px]] [[Ranger tab]]\n|-\n|[[File:Master Parachutist badge (United States).svg|80px]] [[Parachutist Badge (United States)|Master Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:SFDiver.PNG|65px]] [[Diver insignia|Special Operations Diver Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Joint Chiefs of Staff seal.svg|90px]] [[Joint Chiefs of Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:United States Army Staff Identification Badge.png|78px]] [[Army Staff Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Brevet Parachutiste.jpg|100px]] French [[Parachutist Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:101st Airborne Division CSIB.png|75px]] [[101st Airborne Division]] [[Combat Service Identification Badge]]\n|-\n|[[File:Distinctive unit insignia of the 506th Infantry Regiment (United States).svg|50px]] [[506th Infantry Regiment (United States)|506th Infantry Regiment]] [[Distinctive Unit Insignia]]\n|-\n|[[File:ArmyOSB.svg|50px]] 10 [[Overseas Service Bar]]s\n|}\n{|\n|{{ribbon devices|number=1|type=oak|ribbon=Defense Distinguished Service ribbon.svg|width=60}} [[Defense Distinguished Service Medal]] with one bronze [[oak leaf cluster]]\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Distinguished Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-48px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-36px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-24px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Distinguished Service Medal (U.S. Army)|Army Distinguished Service Medal]] with three oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=US Defense Superior Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=60}}<span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-42px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span><span style=\"position:relative; top:0; left:-30px; display:inline-block; width:0;\">[[File:Bronze oakleaf-3d.svg|14px]]</span> [[Defense Superior Service Medal]] with two bronze oak leaf clusters\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|type=oak|ribbon=Legion of Merit ribbon.svg|width=60}}<sp